# Secrets must never leave the machine through git or chat

## The rule

- **Never** write a real API key, token, JWT secret, DB password or OAuth client
  secret into any file that is (or could become) tracked by git.
- **Never** echo a real secret back to the user in chat or commit messages.
  If you need to confirm a value changed, print the key name only, e.g.
  `GEMINI_API_KEY=<REDACTED>`.
- **Never** stage or commit `.env`, `.env.prod`, `.env.local`, `*.pem`, `*.key`,
  or any backup of them (`.bak`, `.backup_*`, copies). They are already in
  `.gitignore` ‚Äî if `git status` shows one, stop and tell the user.
- Treat any key the user pastes into chat as compromised the moment it's
  visible. Use it to update local `.env` and sync to prod, but do not repeat
  it back in a response.

## Where secrets live

| File                           | Tracked? | Purpose                                  |
| ------------------------------ | -------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| `.env`                         | ‚ùå NO    | Local dev secrets on Vadim's machine     |
| `.env.prod` (prod server only) | ‚ùå NO    | Prod secrets at `/opt/propitashka/.env.prod` |
| `.env.example`                 | ‚úÖ yes   | Template, placeholder values only        |
| `.env.production.example`      | ‚úÖ yes   | Template, placeholder values only        |

`.env*` is ignored globally in `.gitignore`, with `!.env.example` and
`!.env.production.example` whitelisted as templates.

## Syncing secrets to prod ‚Äî the only correct flow

```bash
# 1. Edit locally
$EDITOR .env            # or .env.prod.local if staging a prod file

# 2. Push JUST the file to the server over SSH ‚Äî NEVER through git
scp .env.prod root@82.38.66.177:/opt/propitashka/.env.prod

# 3. Restart the container that reads it
ssh root@82.38.66.177 "cd /opt/propitashka && \
  docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml restart backend"
```

For surgical single-key updates, prefer `sed` on the server so the local
machine doesn't need the full prod env:

```bash
ssh root@82.38.66.177 "cd /opt/propitashka && \
  cp .env.prod .env.prod.bak.\$(date +%s) && \
  sed -i -E 's|^GEMINI_API_KEY=.*|GEMINI_API_KEY=NEW_VALUE|' .env.prod && \
  docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml restart backend"
```

## If a secret is already in git history

1. Rotate the secret immediately (new token from the provider).
2. Remove the file from the index: `git rm --cached <file>`.
3. Commit the removal + a `.gitignore` update in the same commit.
4. Tell the user to rewrite history (`git filter-repo`) if the repo is
   public ‚Äî do NOT attempt this unattended.

## Templates that are safe to commit

`.env.example` / `.env.production.example` must only contain:

```env
# ‚ùå BAD ‚Äî real key
GEMINI_API_KEY=AIzaSy...  # ‚Üê real 39-char key goes here, never in git

# ‚úÖ GOOD ‚Äî obvious placeholder
GEMINI_API_KEY=your-gemini-api-key-here
JWT_SECRET_KEY=generate-with-openssl-rand-hex-32
```

A value that looks real (`AIzaSy‚Ä¶`, `sk-‚Ä¶`, `eyJ‚Ä¶`, Telegram `\d+:AA‚Ä¶`) must
never end up in an `*.example` file.

## Pre-commit defense

The repo ships `.githooks/pre-commit` (enabled via `git config core.hooksPath
.githooks`) which blocks commits containing patterns matching Gemini/OpenAI/JWT
and Telegram-bot tokens, plus any file matching `.env` or `.env.prod`. If it
blocks you, FIX the leak ‚Äî do not bypass with `--no-verify`.

## Checklist before any commit involving env/config

- [ ] `git status` shows no `.env*` file (except `*.example`).
- [ ] `git diff --cached` contains no `AIzaSy‚Ä¶`, `sk-‚Ä¶`, `eyJ‚Ä¶`, `\d+:AA‚Ä¶`.
- [ ] Any new key in `.env.example` has an obvious placeholder value.
- [ ] When reporting success to the user, secrets are shown as `<REDACTED>`.
